     <div id="content"> 
      <h1>UA's Efforts Address National STEM Demand </h1> 
      <div class="region region-content"> 
       <div id="block-system-main" class="block block-system"> 
        <div class="content"> 
         <script type="text/javascript">
  window.onload=function() {
    setCaptions();
  }

  function setCaptions() {
    var picwidth=[];
    var containerDiv=document.getElementById('content');
    var dvs=containerDiv.getElementsByTagName('div');
    for(var c=0;c<dvs.length;c++) {
      if(dvs[c].className=='story-image') {
        picwidth[c]=dvs[c].getElementsByTagName('img')[0].clientWidth;
        dvs[c].style.width=picwidth[c]+'px';
      }
    }
  }
</script> 
         <div id="node-58367" class="node node-story node-promoted clearfix" about="/story/ua-s-efforts-address-national-stem-demand" typeof="sioc:Item foaf:Document"> 
          <span class="info"> By La Monica Everett-Haynes, University Relations - Communications | February 18, 2015</span> 
          <div class="view view-story-images view-id-story_images view-display-id-headline view-dom-id-ffb8fc7dc543b25ad1ac378ad8eda63a"> 
           <div class="views-row views-row-1 views-row-odd views-row-first views-row-last"> 
            <div class="field-content">
             <div class="story-image"> 
              <a href="http://uanews.org/sites/default/files/story-images/UA-2001.jpg" title="In recent years, the UA has greatly expanded its efforts to recruit and retain students in the high-demand science, technology, engineering and mathematics fields. " class="colorbox" rel="gallery-node-58367"><img typeof="foaf:Image" src="http://uanews.org/sites/default/files/styles/story-page-headline-800-300/public/story-images/UA-2001.jpg?itok=NKg-MGsi" width="615" height="395" alt="In recent years, the UA has greatly expanded its efforts to recruit and retain students in the high-demand science, technology, engineering and mathematics fields. " title="In recent years, the UA has greatly expanded its efforts to recruit and retain students in the high-demand science, technology, engineering and mathematics fields. "></a> 
              <div class="caption">
               In recent years, the UA has greatly expanded its efforts to recruit and retain students in the high-demand science, technology, engineering and mathematics fields. 
              </div> 
             </div> 
            </div>
           </div> 
          </div> 
          <p class="story-subheading" style="font-style:italic;font-size: 120%;">Under Never Settle, and through a major Association of American Universities initiative, the UA is drastically evolving STEM education to encourage more student interest and retention while increasing the numbers of those with STEM degrees. </p> 
          <div class="content"> 
           <div class="view view-story-images view-id-story_images view-display-id-story_images view-dom-id-148b525c0989c8f5c5f7ad5528821961"> 
           </div> 
           <div class="view view-story-images view-id-story_images view-display-id-story_images_body_headline view-dom-id-6413b0878b6cc1f96002190ac54195bc"> 
            <div class="views-row views-row-1 views-row-odd views-row-first"> 
             <div class="story-image"> 
              <a href="http://uanews.org/sites/default/files/story-images/student_help.jpg" class="colorbox cboxElement" rel="gallery-node-58367" title="The University also has received significant AAU funding to reform STEM education, developing models for enhancing teaching and learning in those fields."> <img typeof="foaf:Image" src="http://uanews.org/sites/default/files/styles/story_body_aspect_ratio_switcher/public/story-images/student_help.jpg?itok=6nC9BLr3" alt="The University also has received significant AAU funding to reform STEM education, developing models for enhancing teaching and learning in those fields." title="The University also has received significant AAU funding to reform STEM education, developing models for enhancing teaching and learning in those fields."> </a> 
              <div class="caption">
               The University also has received significant AAU funding to reform STEM education, developing models for enhancing teaching and learning in those fields.
              </div> 
             </div> 
             <div class="clear"></div> 
            </div>
            <div class="views-row views-row-2 views-row-even views-row-last"> 
             <div class="story-image"> 
              <a href="http://uanews.org/sites/default/files/story-images/_DSC9910.jpg" class="colorbox cboxElement" rel="gallery-node-58367" title="The UA College of Engineering is among the units on campus working to encourage and retain student interest and retention in the STEM fields. The college regularly involves students in applied learning and research activities meant to give them real-world experiences and ties to industry. (Photo: Paul O'Mara)"> <img typeof="foaf:Image" src="http://uanews.org/sites/default/files/styles/story_body_aspect_ratio_switcher/public/story-images/_DSC9910.jpg?itok=TQsaIdH6" alt="The UA College of Engineering is among the units on campus working to encourage and retain student interest and retention in the STEM fields. The college regularly involves students in applied learning and research activities meant to give them real-world experiences and ties to industry. (Photo: Paul O'Mara)" title="The UA College of Engineering is among the units on campus working to encourage and retain student interest and retention in the STEM fields. The college regularly involves students in applied learning and research activities meant to give them real-world experiences and ties to industry. (Photo: Paul O'Mara)"> </a> 
              <div class="caption">
               The UA College of Engineering is among the units on campus working to encourage and retain student interest and retention in the STEM fields. The college regularly involves students in applied learning and research activities meant to give them real-world experiences and ties to industry. (Photo: Paul O'Mara)
              </div> 
             </div> 
             <div class="clear"></div> 
            </div> 
           </div> 
           <div class="field field-name-body field-type-text-with-summary field-label-hidden">
            <div class="field-items">
             <div class="field-item even" property="content:encoded">
              <p>A new generation of global challenges is upon us with needs such as creating better and more specialized medications, making renewable energy more accessible, improving cybersecurity and enhancing food security.</p> 
              <p>The U.S. requires more highly trained professionals in science, technology, engineering and mathematics, or STEM, to innovate the ideas, organizations and industries necessary to address such challenges.</p> 
              <p>The U.S. Department of Commerce projected that, for a period spanning 2008 and 2018, jobs in STEM would see a growth rate 1.7 times faster than non-STEM positions — a 17 percent increase within STEM.</p> 
              <p>In response to the growing demand for such professionals, the Obama administration has charged higher-education institutions with graduating 1 million more students within the four disciplines.</p> 
              <p>The University of Arizona already graduates STEM students at a rate higher than the national average, and the number of graduates in related fields continues to increase on campus, said <strong>Gail Burd</strong>, the UA's senior vice provost for academic affairs.</p> 
              <p>In 2013, the UA graduated 1,271 undergraduates with STEM degrees or 19.6 percent of all bachelor's degrees — up from 17.7 percent in 2003 with 945 graduates. The national average for bachelor's degrees awarded in STEM generally falls between 15 and 17 percent, according to the most recent data available from the National Science Foundation.</p> 
              <p>Building on its strengths in STEM education and under the charge of <a href="http://neversettle.arizona.edu/"><strong>Never Settle</strong></a>, the UA's strategic plan, University faculty and staff have begun to introduce new approaches to maintaining students' interest in STEM and supporting them to degree completion. Also, aligned with the University's 100% Engagement initiative, STEM-related programs often ensure that students have early and regular workforce development training during their time at the UA.&nbsp;</p> 
              <p>In addition to supporting pipeline-building efforts with K-12 and community partners, the UA in 2013 became one of only eight U.S. institutions chosen to be part of a nationwide initiative led by the Association of American Universities to reform teaching and learning in STEM.</p> 
              <p>With the grant, the UA has spent nearly two years introducing active-learning classes early in students' academic careers at the UA.</p> 
              <p>"What we are trying to do is follow best practices to improve the number of students who graduate in STEM," Burd said during an Arizona Board of Regents meeting this month. Burd is principal investigator on the UA's AAU grant, which is funded by the Leona M. and Harry B. Helmsley Charitable Trust.</p> 
              <p>Research indicates that STEM students engaged in active, relevant classroom teachings perform better, think more critically, devise better solutions and continue in their STEM education.&nbsp;</p> 
              <p>"Hundreds of research studies have shown that active teaching practices improve learning in STEM, but there is not a lot going on in the classrooms across the nation using these teaching practices," Burd said. "So, our challenge is to help faculty begin using these practices."</p> 
              <p>Informed by that evidence, the UA has introduced dramatic changes in several foundational courses in STEM, and collaborative learning spaces and new professional development opportunities for faculty.</p> 
              <p>"This is STEM education reform," Burd said, "and it has been very strong at the UA for some time."</p> 
              <p><strong>Rethinking Teaching and Learning</strong></p> 
              <p>Since the UA received the AAU grant, faculty members such as&nbsp;<strong>Ed Prather</strong>, a UA associate professor of astronomy, have introduced STEM-focused faculty learning communities, training more than 80 faculty on ways to adopt effective active-learning teaching strategies.</p> 
              <p>Also, the UA's Collaborative Learning Space, <a href="http://uanews.org/story/a-different-kind-of-space-launch"><strong>formally introduced</strong></a> in October, is designed to support faculty in their shift to more active in-class interactions. It is the early implementation of an important idea: Faculty and administrators expect to see more of these restructured classroom spaces across campus.</p> 
              <p>"A term we often use is that there is a 'coalition of the willing,' which is a group of faculty members who have been redesigning classes, coordinating labs, who are nationally known for their engaged teaching and who teach workshops around the country," Burd said. "We are trying to increase the number of faculty in the coalition of the willing."</p> 
              <p>In fact, the UA's AAU-supported efforts are closely aligned with the President's Council on Advisors on Science and Technology, which is advocating for nationwide improvements in instruction for the benefit of increased student retention and bachelor's degree attainment in STEM.</p> 
              <p>"In academia, when we try to increase the expertise of a group of students or faculty, we all too often employ the age-old instructional model we have always used: the lecture," Prather said, adding that getting students to actively and deeply engage with course topics is the major shift in reformed college STEM teaching.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p> 
              <p>"If faculty's teaching beliefs are exemplified by what they do in the classroom, it appears most believe it is necessary for students to witness an expert perform derivations and solve end-of-the-chapter problems in order to efficiently gain expertise — but that's not true," Prather said.</p> 
              <p>"In fact, there is little about that experience that models what experts actually do or what would benefit students the most. These uninspiring classroom experiences are at the heart of what drives so many smart, high-quality students to leave their STEM pursuits."&nbsp;</p> 
              <p>As faculty change from being purely lecturers to serving as mentors and coaches, instructors such as engineering professor&nbsp;<a href="http://uanews.org/videos/classroom-innovator-paul-blowers"><strong>Paul Blowers</strong></a> find that they are having fun rather than dreading the classroom. It's rewarding, they say, to see students collaborate on solving real-world problems, work with actual data and critically evaluate case studies — exactly the type of skills the workforce demands.</p> 
              <p>This approach to teaching also responds to the needs of students who, according to research, increasingly demand that what they experience in school be relevant to their personal and professional lives.</p> 
              <p>"Yes, you must still cover all of the course content, but this changes the purpose of the lecture," said Prather, who has trained thousands of faculty across the nation in active learning strategies over the last two decades. "During the typical lecture, the faculty member is doing all the work, but in the active classroom, the hard work is placed where it belongs — squarely on the shoulders of the students."</p> 
              <p>Already, Prather and others at the UA have found numerous benefits associated with the adoption of active-learning strategies. The shift can result in performance at least one letter grade higher than students achieve in traditional, lecture-driven courses.</p> 
              <p>And researchers have come upon two additional significant findings: Active learning benefits students regardless of their background or earlier academic performance, and students are more readily retained in STEM when such practices are adopted. As the U.S. falls below countries such as China, Germany, France, Japan and Canada in graduating undergraduates with science and engineering degrees, such findings serve as motivation to expand active learning, Prather said.</p> 
              <p><strong>Preparing Students to Be Scientists</strong></p> 
              <p>In Arizona, computer and mathematical occupations and engineering jobs are expected to see strong growth at least through 2020, according to Arizona Department of Statistics <a href="https://laborstats.az.gov/employment-forecasts"><strong>data</strong></a>.</p> 
              <p>Positions in the state expected to see the greatest demand, with anticipated growth at 25 percent or more, include information security analysts, statisticians, biomedical engineers, civil engineers, and health and safety engineers.</p> 
              <p>Beyond the classroom, the UA has numerous programs that support pipeline-building and workforce-readiness efforts in STEM.</p> 
              <p>The UA has launched the <a href="http://stem.arizona.edu/"><strong>STEM Learning Center</strong></a>, presenting a streamlined process to encourage collaboration among&nbsp;campus, educational, community and business partners in southern Arizona. The center was established to enhance the quality of STEM education from preschool through college via support for students and educators.</p> 
              <p>The University also has expanded the access of public and private employers in the Tucson region to UA students in STEM fields with the launch of the Workforce-Ready Master's Fellowship last year. The fellowship&nbsp;provides a financial incentive to attract students interested in pursuing master’s degrees in 44 fields that have immediate needs for educationally advanced workers. Those fields include&nbsp;including aerospace engineering, mining, water, society and policy, and public health.</p> 
              <p>And to ensure that students remain interested in STEM beyond high school, the UA's <a href="http://asems.arizona.edu/"><strong>Arizona Science, Engineering and Mathematics Scholars</strong></a>, or ASEMS,<strong> </strong>program<strong> </strong>targets new UA freshmen and sophomores, providing early academic and social support.&nbsp;</p> 
              <p>The program also helps undergraduates connect with internships and research opportunities with other programs such as the Undergraduate Biology Research Program, Maximizing Access to Research Careers, Research Experiences for Undergraduates and UA/NASA Space Grant programs.&nbsp;In doing so, ASEMS is preparing students to launch their graduate and professional careers in STEM, said <strong>Kimberly Sierra-Cajas</strong>, director of the UA Office of Undergraduate Research.</p> 
              <p>"We are always looking to increase experiences of engagement for our students," Sierra-Cajas said, adding that the program is currently raising funds to expand the number of students it supports.</p> 
              <p>The <strong><a href="https://ubrp.arizona.edu/">Undergraduate Biology Research Program</a></strong>, or UBRP, is one of the UA's signature undergraduate research programs and also encourages STEM participation among high school students and undergraduates in Tucson and other parts of the state.</p> 
              <p><strong>Victoria Farrar</strong>, a UA Honors College senior studying chemistry and ecology and evolutionary biology, said it has been valuable to participate in scholarly work — and that her experience has motivated her to remain invested in STEM.</p> 
              <p>"If I hadn't joined UBRP, I probably wouldn't have considered going into scientific research because I wouldn't be sure how rewarding it could be," Farrar said. "Having these years of experience ahead of time makes me feel so much more confident that I can go on to contribute to a scientific field."</p> 
             </div>
            </div>
           </div> 
